parole denials a cause for second guessing stanford law school stanford law school search utility navigation test directory news center library events publications contact & maps information for prospective students alumni employers current students faculty & staff news center parole denials a cause for second guessing go back publication date september 30 2011 source the recorder author kate moser the california supreme court in 2008 attempted to clarify how much power the executive branch has to deny parole to the more than 32000 lifer inmates serving time in california judging by the dozens of published and unpublished conflicting and sometimes heated court of appeal rulings since then it appears the court failed it's set to take another stab at it in a case set for oral argument monday gray davis reversed almost all lifer parole grants when he was governor schwarzenegger reversed about 60 percent and remanded 20 percent to the board for further review in his first months in office gov jerry brown has reversed at the lowest rate of the three according to a study on parole for lifers published this month by the stanford criminal justice center related faculty none related stanford criminal justice center scjc cloudy 51 f 2012 stanford university system requirements help virtual tour
